The paper deals with optimization problems related to set functions, matroids, and graph density, which are all topics in the area of theoretical computer science. Specifically, the paper considers the problem of finding the densest subset subject to co-matroid constraints, which is a problem in discrete optimization and falls under the category of algorithms and data structures (cs.DS). The paper also involves the study of monotone supermodular set functions, which is a topic in combinatorial optimization and falls under the category of graph theory (cs.GT). Additionally, the paper uses techniques from information theory (cs.IT) and machine learning (cs.LG) to derive its results. Finally, the paper may also be relevant to the area of computational complexity (cs.CC) since it shows that the problem of finding the densest subset subject to co-matroid constraints is NP-hard.
